	<!-- 
	ConfigPath SharedConfigPath and UserConfigPath specifies where settings, queue and other runtime data should be saved.
	Relative paths are relative to the FlylinkDC++ executable.
	You may use the following variables, which are interpreted on a per-user basis:

	%[APPDATA] - Application data, typically "C:\Users\[user profile name]\Application Data".
	%[LOCAL_APPDATA] - Local application data, typically "C:\Users\[user profile name]\Local Settings\Application data".
	%[COMMON_APPDATA] - Common application data, typically "C:\Users\All Users\Application data".
	%[PERSONAL] - My documents.

	* Note: Folder %[APPDATA], %[LOCAL_APPDATA], and %[PERSONAL] are only available to the user [user profile name].
	Folder %[COMMON_APPDATA] available to all users.

	

	%[PROGRAM_FILESX86] - Program files folder for 32 bit app. (only in 64 bit OS), typically "C:\Program Files (x86)".
	%[PROGRAM_FILES] - Program files folder, typically "C:\Program Files".

	* Note: Folder %[PROGRAM_FILESX86] and %[PROGRAM_FILES] available to all users read-only,
	and users in the group "Administrators" and they are available yet on write.



	* Note: On Windows XP, the path containing the "Users"
	should be changed in the way of containing the "Documents and Settings".
	Example "C:\Users\<username>\Application Data"
	should read as "C:\Documents and Settings\<username>\Application Data".
	
	All % variables from strftime with the current time: 
	http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/en-us/vclib/html/_crt_strftime.2c_.wcsftime.asp


	This example illustrates the situation when all settings are stored in one folder:
		<ConfigPath>%[APPDATA]\FlylinkDC++\Settings\</ConfigPath>
	
	It is also possible to specify different locations for user configuration files
	and shared configuratoin files (such as resource provider, etc.):
		<UserConfigPath>%[APPDATA]\FlylinkDC++\Settings\</UserConfigPath>
		<SharedConfigPath>%[COMMON_APPDATA]\FlylinkDC++\</SharedConfigPath>
	
	-->
</Boot>

